  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense and is classified as a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by concealing their true origin.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is primarily prosecuted under federal law, particularly the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Severe fines**: Individuals can face fines of up to hundreds of thousands of dollars or more, while businesses may face multimillion-dollar penalties.\n- **Prison sentences**: Convictions can result in up to 20 years in federal prison, depending on the severity of the offense.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: Authorities can seize assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity.\n\nState laws may also impose additional penalties for money laundering. The exact consequences depend on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the specific circumstances of the case. Always consult a legal professional for advice related to specific situations.",
